d:["$","div",null,{"className":"article-enter-delay-3 mb-6 not-prose","children":["$","ul",null,{"className":"space-y-2.5 border-l-4 border-yellow-400/50 pl-4","children":[["$","li","0",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"mRNA cancer vaccines advance in research"}]]}],["$","li","1",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"Misinformation complicates public understanding"}]]}],["$","li","2",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"Timeline for clinical use remains unclear"}]]}]]}]}]
e:["$","div",null,{"className":"article-enter-delay-3 article-prose max-w-none","children":[["$","p",null,{"children":["The race toward mRNA cancer vaccines is accelerating, with scientists reporting rapid progress on treatments designed to help the immune system recognize and destroy tumors. But between the headlines and the laboratory bench lies a gap that matters enormously for patients: these vaccines are not yet approved therapies. They are research-stage interventions, and the distance between \"promising\" and \"proven\" in medicine is measured in years of clinical trials, not press releases.\nAccording to ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://medicalxpress.com","children":"MedicalXpress"}],", researchers are making meaningful strides toward a long-anticipated goal: vaccines that could significantly enhance the body's natural defenses against cancer. The approach builds on mRNA technology that demonstrated its capabilities during the COVID-19 pandemic, but adapting it for cancer presents distinct and complex challenges. Each potential vaccine must be evaluated for safety and efficacy through rigorous clinical trials before any claims about \"transforming treatment\" can be substantiated."]}],"\n",["$","div",null,{"className":"not-prose my-8 pt-6 border-t border-white/10","children":[null,["$","div",null,{"className":"glass-card overflow-hidden mb-4 !hover:transform-none","children":["$","img",null,{"src":"/images/articles/mrna-cancer-vaccines-what-we-know-what-we-don-t/subtitle.jpg","alt":"Evidence Level: Research Stage — Not Clinical Reality","className":"w-full h-auto max-h-[400px] object-cover"}]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-text-secondary italic text-lg leading-relaxed font-medium","children":"Evidence Level: Research Stage — Not Clinical Reality"}]]}],"\n",["$","p",null,{"children":["What we know is that the science is advancing. What we don't know is when — or whether — these vaccines will reach patients in routine clinical practice. The timeline for development and implementation remains unspecified, and early-stage research, however encouraging, does not equal clinical availability. For patients today, this means that mRNA cancer vaccines represent legitimate hope on the horizon, not a treatment option currently accessible.\nThe broader challenge extends beyond the laboratory. Misinformation about mRNA technology continues to circulate widely, as documented by ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.nature.com","children":"Nature"}]," and other scientific outlets, complicating public understanding of what these vaccines actually do and don't do. The evidence grade here is critical: this is research-stage work, not regulatory-approved treatment. Sample sizes in ongoing trials remain necessarily limited, and methodology constraints are part of the process. ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.cancer.gov","children":"The National Cancer Institute"}]," provides ongoing updates as trials progress, but responsible reporting requires acknowledging the limits of current knowledge."]}]]}]
